06642nam a22010935i 9783110209389DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20082008gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)703213427  a97831102093897 a10.1515/97831102093892doi  a(DE-B1597)35087  a(OCoLC)503441405  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aPN3383.P64bN37 2008eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809.304 2222200aNarrative Unreliability in the Twentieth-Century First-Person Novel /ced. by Elke D'hoker, Gunther Martens. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (338 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNarratologia : Contributions to Narrative Theory ,x1612-8427 ;v140 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume deals with the occurrence and development of unreliable first-person narration in twentieth century Western literature. The different articles in this collection approach this topic both from the angle of literary theory and through a detailed reading of literary texts. By addressing questions concerning the functions, characteristics and types of unreliability, this collection contributes to the current theoretical debate about unreliable narration. At the same time, the collection highlights the different uses to which unreliability has been put in different contexts, poetical traditions and literary movements. It does so by tracing the unreliable first-person narrator in a variety of texts from Dutch, German, American, British, French, Italian, Polish, Danish and Argentinean literature. In this way, this volume significantly extends the traditional ‘canon’ of narrative unreliability. This collection combines essays from some of the foremost theoreticians of unreliability (James Phelan, Ansgar Nünning) with essays from experts in different national traditions. The result is a collection that approaches the ‘case’ of narrative unreliability from a new and more varied perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aFictiony20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFirst person narrativexHistory and criticism. 0aTruthfulness and falsehood in literature. 4aEzähltheorie. 4aIch-Erzähler. 4aUnzuverlässiger Erzähler. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aFirst-Person Novel.  aNarrative Theory.  aUnreliable Narrator.1 aBadir, Yasmine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernaerts, Lars, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBossche, Bart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrems, Elke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruyn, Dieter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aD'hoker, Elke, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aD’Hoker, Elke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerman, Luc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJedlčiková, Alice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJongeneel, Els, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKindt, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKorthals Altes, Liesbeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrogh Hansen, Per, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartens, Gunther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartens, Gunther, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNünning, Ansgar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPhelan, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1